<TEXT>
chinas tight military lock on the tibetan capital 
of lhasa kept tibetans off the streets and thwarted demonstrations 
on the 30th anniversary of an unsuccessful antichinese uprising 
chinese television said friday that the martial law crackdown in 
the himalayan city had stopped a plot to stage a riot 
the official china news service said a convoy of 72 vehicles and 
more than 1200 troops drove through lhasa on friday in a massive 
show of force the report said the patrol included 10 vehicles with 
automatic rocket guns 
authorities declared martial law tuesday after three days of 
bloody separatist rioting more protests had been expected friday 
the anniversary of the 1959 uprising against chinese rule 
chinas official media said calm had returned to the city of 
70000 and quoted lhasa residents as expressing gratitude for the 
military intervention 
the xinhua news agency quoted a tibetan scholar as saying 
tibetans have a deep hatred for the rioters it depicted 
tibetans offering water straw mattresses tea and shelter to 
chinese troops 
tibetans contacted by telephone however spoke of police 
roundups and a climate of fear they spoke of heavy military 
presence on the streets and said they had been told to remain 
indoors 
one woman said largescale arrests began after most foreigners 
left the city thursday the nightly news friday said more than 30 
rioters had surrendered to police 
foreign tourists were told to leave lhasa when martial law was 
declared two british journalists who entered lhasa as tourists 
during the riots were subjected to interrogations and fined 
a new york man and four swedes reached katmandu nepal from 
lhasa on friday they left the tibetan capital tuesday in a 
fourwheel drive rough terrain vehicle and had to trek through snow 
part of the way 
i feel very lucky to get my passport back from the chinese and 
make my journey safely to katmandu said new yorker russell 
liebman 22 
liebman said on sunday we went to the roof of a house and saw 
the beginning of the demonstration we took lots of photographs we 
noticed some policemen were standing on the roof of another nearby 
house we heard shots 
policemen later stopped them at their hotel and took their film 
and their passports they reported 
we heard shots said one of the swedes who identified 
himself only as pontus the shots fired by the soldiers when i 
looked out from the window you can see a warlike scene once in a 
while dead body being carried in pushcart 
china says the protests left 16 people dead and more than 100 
hurt western travelers say most tibetans place the death toll at 
between 20 and 30 with some estimates much higher 
during the rioting mobs of stonethrowing tibetans ransacked 
chineseowned shops set fire to chinese property and attacked 
government office buildings they demanded independence from china 
and expressed loyalty to the dalai lama 
the march 10 anniversary marks a failed uprising when tens of 
thousands of converged on the dalai lamas palace to prevent what 
they thought was a chinese military attempt to kidnap him 
a week later the chinese allegedly fired two mortar shells into 
the palace grounds and the dalai lama and his family fled secretly 
to india the chinese army moved in to destroy the tibetan 
resistance killing at least hundreds 
</TEXT>
