<TEXT>
district of columbia delegate walter fauntroy 
could become the first congressman investigated by a special 
prosecutor if attorney general dick thornburgh approves 
the justice departments criminal division on friday asked 
thornburgh to appoint an independent counsel to investigate a 
possible payrollpadding scheme involving fauntroy the districts 
nonvoting delegate to the house 
the request came after a threemonth fbi investigation into 
allegations that thomas john savage the son of rep gus savage 
dill did little or no work in fellow democrat fauntroys office 
david runkel a spokesman for thornburgh said the request had 
been submitted but the attorney general had not yet reviewed the 
report runkel added that he did not know when thornburgh would 
decide on the case 
the appointment would be authorized under an order issued last 
august by thenattorney general edwin meese iii setting up the 
procedure to deal with charges of wrongdoing against members of 
congress officials of the executive branch of the federal 
government can be subject to investigation by special prosecutors 
under a separate law and meese himself was twice investigated by 
independent counsels 
in the fauntroy case savage earned 21398 while on fauntroys 
payroll between september 1987 and june 1988 during that time the 
younger savage also swore in notarized illinois election documents 
that he was living full time in chicago where he was running for a 
state house of representatives seat 
several law enforcement officials said that the focus of the 
investigation is possible violations of federal fraud laws 
sources familiar with the investigation and speaking on condition 
of anonymity told the associated press that fauntroy and his staff 
have refused to cooperate with the fbi 
we have concluded that there has to be an independent 
prosecutor simply because there are a number of unanswered questions 
out there and we have individuals who wont talk said a justice 
department source 
an independent prosecutor would have the power to subpoena 
fauntroy and his staff to testify before a grand jury about the 
younger savages whereabouts fbi agents conducting the preliminary 
investigation said they did not have the authority to ask for such 
subpoenas 
fauntroy said through a spokeswoman that he had not learned of 
the justice departments action while rep savage did not return 
repeated phone calls to his capitol hill office thomas savage when 
reached in chicago refused to comment 
investigators based their case around records which were also 
obtained by the associated press that suggest the younger savage was 
in chicago while he was on fauntroys payroll the sources said 
among those documents are notarized residency records and 
election petitions the younger savage filed with the illinois board 
of elections last year those records indicated that he was actually 
in chicago assisting his fathers reelection campaign and 
organizing his own run for office while he was on fauntroys office 
payroll the sources said 
if the case continues investigators likely will examine 
fauntroys office records for the past five years to determine 
whether other hiring irregularities have occurred said sources 
familiar with the case 
