<TEXT>
leaders from 24 nations today 
signed a pact asking the united nations to police efforts to curtail 
ozonedestroying chemicals and other air pollutants 
those who signed the accord included king hussein of jordan and 
presidents francois mitterrand of france hosni mubarak of egypt 
daniel arap moi of kenya and robert mugabe of zimbabwe 
the meeting arranged by the dutch government followed an ozone 
conference of 123 nations earlier this week in london at that 
session 20 countries promised to join 33 nations that have already 
agreed to halve emissions of ozonedestroying chemicals by the end 
of the century 
the united states and the 12nation european community have gone 
further they have pledged to try to ban the chemicals called 
chlorofluorocarbons by 1999 if safe alternatives can be developed 
the compounds have widespread use in aerosol spray cans and 
refrigerators as well as in the electronics and plastics industries 
the new pact billed as the hague declaration says the 
united nations should be given authority to set and monitor air 
pollution rules according to a western diplomat familiar with the 
documents contents he spoke on condition of anonymity 
however the proposal would be an agreement in principle without 
legal force on the nations that sign it the diplomat said 
he said the document does not specify whether there should be a 
new un body to fight air pollution or whether the new 
responsibilities should fall to a strengthened un environment 
program which is based in nairobi kenya 
either way he said the united nations would get authority to 
define standards to enhance or guarantee the protection of the 
atmosphere and monitor compliance the diplomat quoted the hague 
document as saying 
the participants at the conference discussed the gradual 
depletion of the delicate ozone shield that protects earth from 
cancercausing solar radiation and the rise in global temperatures 
known as the greenhouse effect 
government leaders at the dutch gathering included west german 
chancellor helmut kohl and premiers felipe gonzalez of spain 
ingvar carlsson of sweden and gro harlem brundtland of norway 
the hague document says the world court should back up un 
efforts to control the chemicals the diplomat said but he 
acknowledged that the court the uns legal arm depends on 
voluntary compliance 
he said details of the proposal will be worked out in the next 
few months and a broader international accord on atmospheric 
pollution is expected to be signed by october any changes in un 
authority would also need approval of the bodys general assembly in 
new york 
</TEXT>
