<TEXT>
in a major report certain to 
stir controversy a governmentappointed commission called saturday 
for an end to all apartheid laws and the creation of voting rights 
for the black majority 
the south african law commission said all attempts at race reform 
were unlikely to succeed unless the government allows the countrys 
28 million blacks to participate fully in national elections 
the commissions report was released one day after the main 
afrikaner church declared for the first time that apartheid is a 
sin the dutch reformed church which includes president pw botha 
and virtually his entire cabinet as congregants also expressed 
guilt for its role in supporting apartheid 
the commission report was the first time a government body called 
for black voting rights although individuals in government have 
made similar statements on occasion 
the commission was appointed by justice minister kobie coetsee in 
1986 and includes officials in the justice department as well as 
some of the countrys senior judges and legal scholars 
the government had no immediate comment on the report 
south africa should draw up a new constitution that guarantees 
individual rights but expressly prohibits racebased group 
rights the report said 
a bill of rights should ban all forms of discrimination include 
the right to appear in court after being arrested and guarantee the 
rights to peaceful protest and participation in political 
organizations the commission said 
under south africas apartheid policies of racial segregation 
the countrys 5 million whites maintain economic and political 
control over the 28 million blacks 
also the governments 33monthold state of emergency allows 
authorities to detain people indefinitely without charge most forms 
of peaceful protest are banned or restricted under the emergency 
regulations 
botha has said repeatedly he will not even discuss the 
possibility of a black majority government he also has said he is 
committed to segregated schools and neighborhoods 
botha is recovering from a stroke suffered jan 18 his heir 
apparent education minister fw de klerk has been depicted as 
more flexible but he appears to agree with botha on most major 
policy issues and his given no indication he would introduce radical 
change 
however the law commission report repeatedly stressed the 
importance of universal franchise to break the political deadlock 
a bill of rights will not be accepted as legitimate if the 
black people in south africa are not given the vote the 
commission said the right to vote is one of the fundamental human 
rights that must be enshrined in any constitution 
the commission said before a new constitution is drawn up the 
present statute book should be purged of discriminatory legislation 
the report cited several legal obstacles to reform 
the countrys 1983 constitution which includes separate houses 
of parliament for whites people of mixed race and people of asian 
descent but not for blacks 
the population registration act which requires all people to be 
classified by race 
the group areas act which segregates neighborhoods by race 
security legislation that allows for detention without trial 
</TEXT>
