as he fled wounded through the jungles of 
cambodia sichan siv never could have imagined that in 13 years he 
would be a top aide to an american president 
for siv 41 deputy assistant to president bush for public 
liaison the term american dream is not a cliche his almost 
unbelievable story is the stuff of movies 
in a symbolic gesture siv opted to start his job feb 13 the 
13th anniversary of his escape from cambodia but he said with a 
smile the highlight of his 4weekold tenure at the white house 
came when he met bush last week and the president pronounced my 
name right 
in his new job one of two deputies in the office siv is bushs 
contact with ethnic and minority groups he deals with issues like 
civil rights education the homeless and refugees 
sivs tortuous path from wounded refugee to presidential aide 
began after the khmer rouge a brutal communist insurgency defeated 
the usbacked government of lon nol in april 1975 
before his escape siv rode a bicycle across cambodia for 20 
days survived in a khmer rouge labor camp eating a bowl of rice a 
day and worked myriad jobs from dawn to dusk 
i dug irrigation canals i plowed land i planted rice i 
harvested rice he said 
he fled cambodia 10 months after the khmer rouge takeover by 
jumping off a timber truck and running through the jungle without 
food for three days until he reached thailand en route he stepped 
on a land mine 
about 15 family members including his mother were among the 
hundreds of thousands of people killed by the pol pot regime 
it was his mother a buddhist whose philosophy helped him 
survive siv said 
the two things she told me are as long as you live you must 
always have hope and happiness is something you cant keep 
unless you give it away those are the basic values of life that i 
have always kept with me he said in an interview 
sivs new life working in an ornate highceilinged office at 
the white house complex seems light years away from the cambodian 
bush 
but siv who dresses in pinstriped suits with suspenders and 
speaks english with an accent keeps mementos nearby native musical 
instruments silver ornaments and books about his native land 
the son of a policeman siv received his high school and college 
