<TEXT>
if stocks are headed for an extended bear market 
a large group of presumably savvy investors is going to be proved 
wrong 
these people top corporate executives directors and major 
shareholders have been voting consistently with their checkbooks 
lately for higher stock prices in the months and years ahead 
the insider buying of the last 16 months is the strongest 
sustained buying trend on record says editor norman fosback in 
the current issue of the insiders a newsletter that tracks the 
activities of what it calls americas most knowledgeable 
investors 
the word insider has been associated with a lot of illegal 
tarding activity in recent years 
what fosback and a good many other analysts track however are 
purchases and sales that top corporate officials report to 
regulators in compliance with the rules 
these people tend to be longerterm investors rather than 
traders since the law provides that they can be forced to give up 
any profits on shares of their own companies held for less than six 
months 
since insiders acquire much of their holdings through private 
means exercise of stock options for example their public 
activity naturally involves more selling than buying 
fosback figures that the normal level of purchases is 35 
percent of total transactions 
according to his calculations insider buying has been above that 
norm since early 1987 it soared to an unprecedented high after the 
crash in october 1987 and has settled down in the neighborhood of 
50 percent over the past year or so 
the insider indicator simply shows no letup of insider 
buying fosback said until the indicator eases down into the 
selling zone below 35 percent expect most market surprises to be 
pleasant ones 
skeptics about the usefulness of this indicator point out that 
insiders were enthusiastically buying through the weeks and months 
that led up to the crash in the fall of 1987 
fosback who readily acknowledged at the time that the insiders 
completely missed the crash says the experience showed that 
this indicator like all others cant be considered infallible 
but the idea of tracking insider transactions gets an 
enthusiastic endorsement from peter lynch the celebrated manager of 
the fidelity magellan fund in the recently published book one up 
on wall street he wrote with john rothchild 
theres no better tipoff to the probable success of a stock 
than that people in the company are putting their own money into 
it lynch writes 
when insiders are buying like crazy you can be certain that 
at a minimum the company will not go bankrupt in the next six 
months 
long term theres another important benefit when management 
owns stock then rewarding the shareholders becomes a first 
priority whereas when management simply collects a paycheck then 
increasing salaries becomes a first priority 
since bigger companies tend to pay bigger salaries to 
executives theres a natural tendency for corporate wageearners to 
expand the business at any cost often to the detriment of 
shareholders this happens less often when management is heavily 
invested in shares 
lynch does not advocate using insider purchases as an indicator 
for quick trading profits indeed he does not advocate seeking 
quick trading profits at all since he does not think it feasible to 
try to outguess what the market as a whole is going to do 
instead he advocates concentrating on choosing stocks of 
companies that have good business reasons why they might gain 
greater popularity in the future on wall street 
thus he says if the stock prices drops after the insiders 
have bought so that you have a chance to buy it cheaper than they 
did so much the better for you 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

