sallie bingham insists she doesnt want pity 
but her book passion and prejudice a family memoir knopf 
2295 an account of the binghams of kentucky and her role in the 
breakup of one of the last great newspaper dynasties in the nation 
reads like a 500page plea for sympathy 
i dont want anybody to feel sorry for me i would think that 
was ridiculous she said in a recent interview i mean i think 
that they might feel regret that the bingham family behaved the way 
they have to feel sorry for me would be ludicrous because having 
this money gives me all kinds of wonderful opportunity that most 
people would never have 
the money to which bingham referred is the 62 million she 
received when her father barry bingham sr announced in 1986 that 
he was selling the family holdings the courierjournal and the 
louisville times newspapers a louisville tv station and a printing 
company to settle family squabbles over control of the empire 
the bingham family is to kentucky what the kennedys are to the 
rest of the nation their great wealth and good works gave them an 
almost mythical status in the state the courierjournal which has 
won eight pulitzer prizes was distributed throughout kentucky and 
had national influence for many years it was ranked among the top 
10 newspapers in the country the family had a liberal reputation a 
strong civil rights record and spent millions and millions on arts 
education and conservation 
bingham 52 whose announcement that she wanted to sell her 15 
percent share of the holdings was believed to have been the genesis 
of the family dispute rejected the familys buyout offers as too 
low and held out for an outside offer passion and prejudice is 
her attempt to remove the villain label cast upon her since her 
father sold the papers to the gannett co for a reported 4358 
million 
she said she finds it a little bewildering that the family with 
whom she is now very publicly estranged holds her responsible for 
the dissolution of the empire 
as you know i was a minority shareholder she said so 
its a little impossible for me to accept responsiblity for the sale 
of those companies that was really fathers decision but 
people seem to want to seek a scapegoat which is what i see 
happening to women a good deal in her book she said she didnt 
know he had decided to sell the papers until a reporter telephoned 
her at a restaurant and read her the press statement 
her memoir contends that for generations the bingham men have 
muzzled the bingham women relegating them to serving tea and 
planning cocktail parties while the patriarchs ruled the 
communications empire 
although many of her claims of male chauvinism might be justified 
her brother barry bingham jr demanded in 1983 that all the 
bingham women resign from the companys board of directors or he 
would resign as publisher of the papers the feminist rhetoric she 
espouses in the book and in her interview sounds less like 
impassioned belief than windowdressing to conceal a vendetta 
against the rest of the family for myriad grievances 
since passion and prejudice was published last month the 
other members of the bingham family her brother mother and sister 
her father died last august have retorted with an impressive 
document mailed out to book reviewers nationwide chronicling what it 
claims are some 300 errors in the book 
some of the errors the bound and painstakingly appendixed 
document cites are petty and sniping such as one pointing out that 
the authors reference to her brothers blond mustache in a 
particular passage is incorrect because he didnt grow it until 
later 
others are more serious in her book bingham says her parents 
asked her to return to editing the papers book page a job shed 
held briefly while the regular editor took a short leave of absence 
she accepted and the editor was reassigned to another position the 
bingham document states that it was sallie bingham who pressured her 
father into transferring the book page editor so she could 
permanently have the job 
in fact shirley williams the book page editor who lost her job 
has filed a libel suit against bingham and her publishers claiming 
that the false intentional and malicious passage has damaged 
her professional reputation williams is now a reporter for the 
courierjournals indiana weekly bingham would not comment on the 
lawsuit but said her lawyers are reviewing it 
the sections of passion and prejudice that most offend the 
family are sallie binghams account of her grandfather judge robert 
worth bingham she believes the judge as he was always called had 
syphilis and suggests in a surprisingly unsubstantiated chapter that 
he may have hastened the death of his second wife mary lily kenan 
flagler heiress to the standard oil fortune and at the time the 
richest woman in the united states the 5 million the judge 
received from a codicil to her will enabled him to buy the 
newspapers 
bingham now lives in prospect ky where she devotes her time to 
the kentucky foundation for women an organization that funds arts 
projects that promote social change either overtly or covertly 
she started the foundation three years ago bankrolling it with 10 
million of her fortune 
she also edits a literary quarterly she started the american 
voice which she calls a radical feminist publication she said she 
tells contributors send us the essay you thought no one would 
ever publish 
despite her life of wealth sallie binghams life has not been 
easy her oldest and youngest brothers worth and robert bingham 
died in freak accidents only two years apart in the mid1960s and 
she had two failed marriages as she struggled with a fiction and 
playwriting career before meeting her third husband 
i dont think any amount of money can save you from 
experience she observed 
