<TEXT>
about a quarter million lands end customers 
recently got something extra besides catalogs or the clothing theyd 
requested from the mailorder company 
they received letters warning them that possible changes in the 
way state sales taxes are collected could jeopardize the convenience 
and raise the cost of shopping at home 
in an attempt to rally consumers to its cause lands end urged 
customers to write their senators or representatives in washington 
and obligingly provided a sample letter and a list of every states 
delegation to the house of representatives 
the lands end mailings are the latest salvo in a longsimmering 
squabble pitting many mailorder merchants against local storefront 
retailers who contend the direct mail outfits gain an unfair 
advantage by not having to collect most state sales taxes 
the tensions have been escalating in recent years as mail sales 
have mushroomed the proliferation of tollfree 800 numbers changes 
in lifestyles growth in the number of people holding 
nationallyrecognized credit cards and an assortment of 
technological and demographic trends have boosted the direct 
marketing business 
mailorder sales volume totaled 112 billion in 1987 according 
to industry estimates up 12 percent from 1986s 100 billion the 
business is expected to expand at similar rates in future years 
surpassing the more modest growth of instore sales 
at issue is the salestaxfree status of some merchandise sent 
through the mail ranging from apparel ordered from traditional 
catalog companies to trinkets bought from television purveyors 
fortyfive states and washington dc have sales taxes on their 
books along with use taxes that theoretically give them the 
right to charge sales tax when their residents buy something outside 
their homestate borders and bring it home to use it 
for practical purposes the use taxes have not been enforced 
except in circumstances spelled out in a 1967 supreme court decision 
the court held that a vendor cannot be required to collect taxes 
from an outofstate customer unless the seller has a business 
presence in the state 
this is why retailers like sears roebuck and co or jc penney 
co inc that run mailorder businesses and have stores nationwide 
charge taxes on most mailorder goods while companies like lands 
end do not lands end only has to collect sales tax for the states 
of illinois iowa and wisconsin the places where the dodgeville 
wisbased company has offices or warehouses 
attempts have been made over the years to empower states to 
require more mailorder outlets to collect taxes on shipments made 
to customers in other states 
various legislation has been proposed on the subject in past 
congressional sessions but none garnered enough backing to push 
them into law 
but this session of congress may be different one bill that 
would augment states taxcollection powers already has been 
introduced in the senate and another is expected soon in the house 
of all the issues currently facing state governments the use tax 
matter is one on which there is true consensus says james l 
martin director of statefederal relations for the national 
governors association 
he said the states lost an estimated 29 billion in revenue in 
one year recently because they couldnt enforce the use tax fully 
enough capturing the unrealized tax revenue which is rising by at 
least 10 percent a year is appealing to states that have watched 
funding from federal sources dwindle 
but the revenue element is given secondary billing to competitive 
issues by a broad coalition that is lobbying to broaden state 
taxcollection power besides state governments the coalition 
comprises groups of retailers and organized labor 
retailers see it as an unfair playing field says martin 
main street retailers are paying all sorts of taxes such as 
property and they also must collect the state sales taxes 
our basic premise is that its important to level the tax piece 
of the playing field martin says 
direct marketers dont see it that way they contend they would 
be burdened with costly administrative duties such as setting up 
systems for tallying sales tax charges and publishing lists of state 
sales tax rates in their catalogs 
many companies wouldnt be able to afford the cost according to 
robert levering of the direct marketing association 
previously proposed legislation exempted from tax collection 
tasks any mailorder operations that sold less than 125 million 
worth of merchandise a year that would include about 95 percent of 
all us direct merchants 
but levering said the threshold could inhibit growth of small 
outfits and hurt midsize to large direct merchants already 
operating on thin margins 
for mailorder shoppers the use tax could have some annoying 
consequences 
people who pay for merchandise by check would have to calculate 
sales tax when they send in their money for instance an estimated 
56 percent of the 88 million customers each year who shop through 
catalogs pay by check 
that inconvenience would come on top of possibly higher prices as 
mailorder companies upgrade their systems to handle tax collection 
in the end mailorder companies will have to pass these 
expenses along to you the lands end letter to customers 
statedyou will pay higher prices 
</TEXT>
