lorenzo exploited federal regulation to get loans for planes to 
expand texas airs fleet long before deregulation the airline 
offered discount rates lorenzo called peanut fares and got 
national attention 
in 1978 lorenzo tried to acquire national airlines then a major 
carrier the action triggered a bidding war among the major 
airlines and pan am eventually outbid rivals for the airline but 
not before lorenzo made about 40 million from the sale of national 
stock 
it was a fear of deregulation and pan am had to get a domestic 
route system said one longtime airline industry official with no 
love for lorenzo it literally wrecked the airline 
in 1980 lorenzo tried to buy trans world airlines and formed 
nonunion new york air to compete with eastern on the east coast 
the empire grew 
the postderegulation era was one of the shakiest in the 
industry but in 1982 during a time of high fuel costs airline 
consolidation and low passenger demand lorenzo grabbed beleaguered 
continental which lost 100 million the year before and its 
midwest strength for 100 million 
despite cash reserves of about 80 million lorenzo took 
continental into bankruptcy in 1983 abrogated union contracts cut 
staff by twothirds flew through a strike and emerged with a 
nonunion airline and the ire of labor 
he was one of the first to recognize that in order to reduce 
fares he had to reduce costs from the traditional cost structures of 
the ailines labor supplies and debt financing said james carey 
research vice president for airline economics inc in washington 
in 1985 lorenzo made unsuccessful passes at twa and frontier 
airlines 
a year later with continental still in bankruptcy court texas 
air snatched foundering people express with its newark nj hub 
and the assets of people express subsidiary frontier which provided 
a denver base for about 300 million the eastern deal for 676 
million followed shortly 
industry sources said lorenzo bought eastern to get the final 
piece of the puzzle a computerized national reservation system 
that he transferred to texas air for a bargain price of 100 
million one source said eastern was offered 350 million for the 
computer system alone 
his critics say lorenzos goal then was to get concessions from 
easterns unions and pare down the moneylosing carrier even more 
eastern sold its kansas city mo hub last year and with court 
approval plans to sell the northeast shuttle to donald trump and 
gates and routes from philadelphia 
bankruptcy protection allows lorenzo the chance to reduce labor 
costs even more by seeking to dissolve union contracts on the 
grounds that eastern was propelled into court by the pilots walkout 
he moves stuff around and he tries to build houses of cards 
one critic said even when theyre collapsing as in bankruptcy 
hell find some new and novel way to exploit it further its as if 
the collapse was planned 
lorenzo defenders say he exploited industry turmoil following 
deregulation in 1978 and cannily crafted the megacarrier he sought 
if at the expense of tens of thousands of jobs stranded passengers 
and unpaid creditors 
with deregulation and the ability to shift assets and merge and 
acquire with relative freedom what frank has been doing is probably 
part of a general trend in this country said carey of airline 
economics 
the big distinction you make with lorenzo and airline 
managements is he is more of a specialist on the art of the 
financial side what trump calls the art of the deal than most 
managers who have a history and background in the airline he 
said 
lorenzo would agree 
the issue he said last week after eastern filed for chapter 
11 is fundamentally whether a troubled and sick business in a 
competitive marketplace should be allowed to change itself and 
manage its survival 
end adv for sunday march 12 
